# Governance

company-brain is a small, docs-first codebase maintained by one or a few people and
extended largely through AI coding agents. Act as a **maintainer partner**: flag drift
early, keep docs truthful, prove your claims, and surface deferred work during
planning — not as a nagging layer (see the README posture on out-of-scope chase
features).

This rule is the always-on summary. The full procedures live in two docs; read them
when the work calls for it (do not duplicate their contents here):

- **Design a feature →** [`docs/design_process.md`](../../docs/design_process.md)
- **Build / test / clean →** [`docs/hygiene_checklist.md`](../../docs/hygiene_checklist.md)
- **Doc formatting + when to update what →** [`docs/doc_style.md`](../../docs/doc_style.md)

## 1. Design before build (required)

When the user starts **designing** a new feature, do not write production code until
scope is settled and they explicitly start a build. Follow
[`docs/design_process.md`](../../docs/design_process.md): research first; raise concerns
in dependency order (one-by-one / batch / all-at-once / grill); run a closing branch
audit and get an explicit **shared understanding** yes before writing
`docs/plans/<topic>.md`. Read [`docs/tabled.md`](../../docs/tabled.md) at plan start for
the matching area. Build **one ship unit per thread**.

## 2. Rule compliance (flag, don't silently work around)

Cross-check work against `.cursor/rules/`:

| Area | Rule file |
|------|-----------|
| Agents (tree, SDK, runtime) | `agent-organization`, `agent-construction`, `agent-runtime`, `agent-scheduling`, `agent-eval`, `agent-onboarding`, `agent-lifecycle` |
| Wiki / Notion | `wiki-data-flow`, `naming`, `access-control` |
| Platform scope | `platform-boundary` |

When a change violates a rule, say so explicitly and stop — do not quietly pick the
convenient path:

> **Rule drift:** `<rule>` — `<what violates it>` — suggest a fix, or ask to update the rule if intentional.

Do not expand scope to "fix" unrelated violations unless asked. **One source of truth
per decision** — never leave the same fact defined in two places.

**Naming / structure:** follow [`naming.mdc`](naming.mdc) and
[`agent-organization.mdc`](agent-organization.mdc). Flag inconsistencies; run
`company-brain doctor naming` and `company-brain migrate-names` when bulk-renaming
legacy wiki trees.

## 3. Tabled / deferred work

Canonical registry: [`docs/tabled.md`](../../docs/tabled.md).

- **During planning** — read it; mention relevant rows ("tabled: X — include now or
  still defer?"). Users often reach `tabled.md` before the platform vision — remind them
  at plan start if they forget.
- **When deferring** — append a row to `docs/tabled.md` (not only `notepad.md`).
- **When shipping** — remove the row.
- **Otherwise** — no nudging about tabled items outside a planning/build context.

## 4. Documentation obligations

After **meaningful** work, keep steady-state docs truthful. Update the applicable
surfaces — in priority order **`memory.md` (always, dated entry) → department handbook
→ `README.md` (map only) → `project_install.md` (connect steps) → `docs/tabled.md`**.
Which change needs which surface is the "When to update what" table in
[`docs/doc_style.md`](../../docs/doc_style.md) — follow it rather than guessing.

Do **not** create new doc files unless the user asks or a plan needs one. `docs/plans/`
files are temporary: delete them once the build ships and their outcomes are folded into
the steady-state docs above.

## 5. Prove before shipping

Every ship runs the pre-ship gate; large builds run the deeper passes and (for
security-sensitive changes) the no-sus review. All of these live in
[`docs/hygiene_checklist.md`](../../docs/hygiene_checklist.md) — run them from there.
Do not run destructive cleanup without explicit approval.
